        introduction: "Longwy is an emblematic town in northern Meurthe-et-Moselle, at the tip of the Three Borders Country where France, Belgium and Luxembourg meet. Its upper town, fortified by Vauban in 1679, has been UNESCO World Heritage listed since 2008 as part of the Vauban fortifications network (one of twelve major sites). The hexagonal Place d'Armes, surrounded by cut-stone military buildings, is a masterpiece of classical military urbanism. Longwy is also inseparable from Lorraine's steelmaking history: the Longwy steelworks, founded in 1880, sustained generations of workers from across Europe, creating a unique multicultural melting pot. The closure of the last plants in the 1980s-2000s deeply marked the town, which is reinventing itself today thanks to its strategic border position. Longwy enamels, colourful faience with geometric patterns on a characteristic blue background, have been a recognised craft tradition since 1798, exported worldwide.",
